Addendum 2026-05-14 — restart-persistence coverage
==================================================

The "all four lifecycle calls return HTTP 200 AND proposal state persists
across `create_app()` restart" task-list item in issue #1187 was not
demonstrated by the original verification log above (the captured run
exercises the lifecycle once but never restarts the trip-planner app).

Restart-persistence is now covered by a focused pytest at
`tests/app/test_proposal.py::test_proposal_state_persists_across_create_app_restart`.
The test:

1. Sets `TRIP_PLANNER_DATABASE_URL` to a per-test SQLite file under tmp.
2. Builds `create_app()` instance A, runs the full proposal submit +
   evaluation lifecycle via TestClient against fixture HTTP responses
   (the same fixtures used by the existing persisted-lifecycle tests).
3. Closes the first TestClient (drops the SQLAlchemy session factory
   reference and exits the FastAPI lifespan).
4. Builds a fresh `create_app()` instance B against the SAME SQLite file
   (no `reset_database_state`), signs the same user back in via
   `/api/auth/login`, and asserts the proposal_id, evaluation_id, and
   summary submission_status match the values persisted by instance A.

This proves restart-persistence at the trip-planner layer without
requiring live TPP infrastructure (which is one-shot and not re-runnable
in CI). The live-tpp PASS above and this fixture-backed restart test
together address both halves of the original task-list item.

Run with:

    pytest tests/app/test_proposal.py::test_proposal_state_persists_across_create_app_restart -v

Expected result: PASSED. A regression where proposal state were held only
in process memory (e.g. a non-persistent cache promoted to the proposal
source-of-truth) would surface here as a 404 / empty proposal payload
from the second app instance.
